Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

["Bluetongue (BT) is an infectious, non-contagious, vector-borne viral disease that affects wild and domestic ruminants. Midges of just a few species in the genus _Culicoides_ (the insect host transmit bluetongue virus (BTV) among susceptible ruminants, having become infected by feeding on viraemic animals (the vertebrate host). In many parts of the world infection has a seasonal occurrence. BTV does not establish persistent infections in ruminants, and survival of BTV in the environment is associated with insect factors. Epidemiological systems (episystems) delimited by vector species and their natural history are considered to determine the global distribution of BTV). Recent observations in Europe and the USA indicate that strains of BTV can move between episystems and adapt to different species of vector midges.

Virus may be introduced to a free area via infected insects, live ruminants or in contaminated products that are then transmitted to susceptible ruminants. If appropriate _Culicoides spp._ competent as vectors are present, virus can then be transmitted to other hosts. BTV is not known to cause disease in humans under any conditions." Source: OIE Terrestrial Manual 2019, Chapter 3.1.3 Bluetongue (Infection with Bluetongue virus) https://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/3.01.03_BLUETONGUE.pdf.

Between July and October 2014, Macedonia reported 299 outbreaks of bluetongue serotype 4 to the OIE. The event was resolved on 27 Feb 2015. See event summary and map at https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review/viewsummary?reportid=15782.

According to the current report, the affected population in Brod is mixed, including both sheep and goats. The epidemiological data do not differentiate between them. However, BTV 4 (as most other BTV serotypes) rarely causes clinical signs in goats; sheep, and in particular European mutton breeds as well as other susceptible sheep breeds (e.g. Chios), may be seriously affected, with mortality that may, in some cases, exceeds 20-30 percent. It will be helpful to know whether goats are included among the 9 cases recorded in this flock. If/when vaccination is applied, goats will not be vaccinated. - Mods.CRD/AS

Maps of North Macedonia https://tinyurl.com/y8h7ffb7 and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7564181,65196]
